1
00:01:21,720 --> 00:01:25,354
YOUNG GIRL:
Torch?

2
00:01:25,354 --> 00:01:27,920
Torch, where are you?

3
00:01:29,654 --> 00:01:31,454
Are you hiding on me?

4
00:01:34,487 --> 00:01:35,788
Torch?

5
00:01:35,788 --> 00:01:37,521
<i>CHIEKO: Near the end
of the 21st century,</i>

6
00:01:37,521 --> 00:01:40,587
<i>my mother and father
and scores of others</i>

7
00:01:40,587 --> 00:01:43,287
<i>left the Earth for a new home.</i>

8
00:01:43,287 --> 00:01:44,254
GIRL: Torch!

9
00:01:47,354 --> 00:01:51,387
<i>CHIEKO: Several years later,
I was born here in L5,</i>

10
00:01:51,387 --> 00:01:53,187
<i>the first city in space.</i>

11
00:01:55,687 --> 00:01:57,621
[SQUAWKING]

12
00:02:03,320 --> 00:02:06,020
<i>The garden
was always my favorite place.</i>

13
00:02:06,020 --> 00:02:07,354
You're a pretty bird.

14
00:02:08,821 --> 00:02:12,154
<i>People said it reminded
them of Earth.</i>

15
00:02:12,154 --> 00:02:14,487
<i>Of course,</i>

16
00:02:14,487 --> 00:02:17,287
<i>I had never actually
been there,</i>

17
00:02:17,287 --> 00:02:21,087
<i>but I could imagine
how beautiful it must be.</i>

18
00:02:23,953 --> 00:02:25,387
Want to make
a wish, Torch?

19
00:02:25,387 --> 00:02:29,254
<i>It's lovely here too,
living among the stars.</i>

20
00:02:47,721 --> 00:02:51,421
<i>Our city is the gateway
to the solar system.</i>

21
00:02:51,421 --> 00:02:55,053
<i>It's home to 10,000 people.</i>

22
00:02:55,053 --> 00:02:56,554
<i>They came here</i>

23
00:02:56,554 --> 00:02:59,087
<i>to follow their dreams
of exploration</i>

24
00:02:59,087 --> 00:03:03,888
<i>and expansion to new worlds.</i>

25
00:03:03,888 --> 00:03:06,888
<i>It takes about five days
to get here from Earth</i>

26
00:03:06,888 --> 00:03:09,854
<i>on the transfer shuttle.</i>

27
00:03:09,854 --> 00:03:14,387
<i>It's routine now,
but it wasn't always so easy.</i>

28
00:03:14,387 --> 00:03:16,754
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Transport data recall.</i>

29
00:03:16,754 --> 00:03:20,287
<i>CHIEKO: The journey began
over a century ago</i>

30
00:03:20,287 --> 00:03:23,621
<i>when our ancestors
took the first small steps</i>

31
00:03:23,621 --> 00:03:25,554
<i>away from their home planet.</i>

32
00:03:35,154 --> 00:03:38,721
<i>They faced
an enormous challenge then:</i>

33
00:03:38,721 --> 00:03:40,120
<i>how to escape the gravity</i>

34
00:03:40,120 --> 00:03:42,888
<i>that held them pinned
to the ground.</i>

35
00:03:46,087 --> 00:03:49,220
<i>They had to design a ship
powerful enough</i>

36
00:03:49,220 --> 00:03:53,187
<i>to lift them into space
and then return them safely</i>

37
00:03:53,187 --> 00:03:55,888
<i>through the searing heat
of the atmosphere</i>

38
00:03:55,888 --> 00:03:57,754
<i>back down to Earth.</i>

39
00:04:01,120 --> 00:04:03,754
<i>There was no fusion power
in those days.</i>

40
00:04:03,754 --> 00:04:05,020
<i>The early technology</i>

41
00:04:05,020 --> 00:04:08,320
<i>used more than
two million pounds of fuel</i>

42
00:04:08,320 --> 00:04:11,320
<i>to launch a small crew
and a few days' supplies</i>

43
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:12,920
<i>into orbit.</i>

44
00:04:52,687 --> 00:04:53,888
<i>ASTRONAUT:
Hey, Houston,</i>

45
00:04:53,888 --> 00:04:55,687
<i>I wish you could see
the view we see</i>

46
00:04:55,687 --> 00:04:57,187
<i>on monitor two.</i>

47
00:04:57,187 --> 00:04:59,187
<i>CHIEKO:
For the first time in
their history,</i>

48
00:04:59,187 --> 00:05:03,187
<i>Earth dwellers saw their home
from the outside.</i>

49
00:05:03,187 --> 00:05:05,354
<i>ASTRONAUT:
It's an incredible
sight, isn't it?</i>

50
00:05:05,354 --> 00:05:06,587
<i>CHIEKO:
Perhaps it was then,</i>

51
00:05:06,587 --> 00:05:09,854
<i>as they gazed upon
its fragile beauty,</i>

52
00:05:09,854 --> 00:05:11,320
<i>they began to see</i>

53
00:05:11,320 --> 00:05:12,987
<i>that instead of competing
with one another,</i>

54
00:05:12,987 --> 00:05:14,421
<i>they could unite</i>

55
00:05:14,421 --> 00:05:18,087
<i>and explore the wonders
of the solar system together.</i>

56
00:05:24,187 --> 00:05:25,888
<i>The first wonder
they discovered</i>

57
00:05:25,888 --> 00:05:27,487
<i>was zero gravity.</i>

58
00:05:29,754 --> 00:05:31,788
<i>Suddenly, people were thrust
into a world</i>

59
00:05:31,788 --> 00:05:34,754
<i>with no up or down.</i>

60
00:05:34,754 --> 00:05:36,621
<i>They had to learn</i>

61
00:05:36,621 --> 00:05:39,287
<i>a completely new way
of living and working</i>

62
00:05:39,287 --> 00:05:41,254
<i>inside their spaceships.</i>

63
00:05:45,554 --> 00:05:47,687
[COSMONAUTS SPEAKING RUSSIAN]

64
00:05:49,888 --> 00:05:51,920
<i>Then the Russians
built a space station</i>

65
00:05:51,920 --> 00:05:54,587
<i>called Mir.</i>

66
00:05:54,587 --> 00:05:56,987
[COSMONAUTS SPEAKING RUSSIAN]

67
00:05:56,987 --> 00:06:00,020
<i>Some early cosmonauts
stayed inside this tiny outpost</i>

68
00:06:00,020 --> 00:06:03,454
<i>for over 400 days.</i>

69
00:06:03,454 --> 00:06:08,521
<i>The actual living space
was only 30 feet long.</i>

70
00:06:08,521 --> 00:06:12,721
<i>Imagine spending a year
in such a small place.</i>

71
00:06:12,721 --> 00:06:15,521
[COSMONAUTS SPEAKING RUSSIAN]

72
00:06:21,788 --> 00:06:23,888
<i>As the millennium began,</i>

73
00:06:23,888 --> 00:06:26,187
<i>the first cautious steps
away from Earth</i>

74
00:06:26,187 --> 00:06:30,487
<i>turned into strides.</i>

75
00:06:30,487 --> 00:06:32,888
<i>Several different countries
working together</i>

76
00:06:32,888 --> 00:06:36,087
<i>designed
a much larger space station.</i>

77
00:06:36,087 --> 00:06:39,754
<i>The parts were made on Earth,
ferried up on spacecraft,</i>

78
00:06:39,754 --> 00:06:42,454
<i>and assembled in orbit.</i>

79
00:06:42,454 --> 00:06:45,687
<i>It took seven years to build.</i>

80
00:06:52,554 --> 00:06:54,721
<i>The people that lived here</i>

81
00:06:54,721 --> 00:07:01,320
<i>were the first to really adapt
to a continuous life in space.</i>

82
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:03,621
<i>It wasn't long
before they were ready</i>

83
00:07:03,621 --> 00:07:05,554
<i>to travel to another planet.</i>

84
00:07:38,788 --> 00:07:42,254
[ELECTRICAL CRACKLING
AND MECHANICAL WHIRRING]

85
00:07:42,254 --> 00:07:44,953
Finally, we reached
the outer planets.

86
00:07:44,953 --> 00:07:47,554
[CRACKLING AND WHIRRING
CONTINUE]

87
00:07:47,554 --> 00:07:52,120
<i>We always sent robot scouts
into new territory first.</i>

88
00:07:52,120 --> 00:07:53,888
<i>They were the builders
and caretakers</i>

89
00:07:53,888 --> 00:07:55,821
<i>of our outposts.</i>

90
00:08:03,087 --> 00:08:06,521
<i>It was the great dream
that people would soon follow</i>

91
00:08:06,521 --> 00:08:08,687
<i>and settle
the outer solar system.</i>

92
00:08:11,320 --> 00:08:15,254
<i>To do that,
we would need a port in space.</i>

93
00:08:15,254 --> 00:08:16,654
<i>It would have to be a place</i>

94
00:08:16,654 --> 00:08:18,987
<i>with very little pull
from gravity</i>

95
00:08:18,987 --> 00:08:23,421
<i>so that ships could come and go
with ease.</i>

96
00:08:23,421 --> 00:08:26,020
<i>And so it was that L5,</i>

97
00:08:26,020 --> 00:08:28,854
<i>a point on the moon's orbit
around the Earth,</i>

98
00:08:28,854 --> 00:08:30,354
<i>was chosen.</i>

99
00:08:32,421 --> 00:08:35,721
<i>Then a master plan
was drawn up,</i>

100
00:08:35,721 --> 00:08:40,454
<i>a grand design
for the first city in space.</i>

101
00:08:44,120 --> 00:08:47,587
<i>Of course, people were used to
Earth's gravity.</i>

102
00:08:47,587 --> 00:08:50,987
<i>To provide something similar,
the living area on L5</i>

103
00:08:50,987 --> 00:08:53,387
<i>would be built
in a mile-wide wing</i>

104
00:08:53,387 --> 00:08:55,387
<i>which rotates once every
minute.</i>

105
00:08:59,487 --> 00:09:01,521
<i>The centrifugal force
from the spin</i>

106
00:09:01,521 --> 00:09:04,387
<i>would produce
artificial gravity.</i>

107
00:09:06,687 --> 00:09:08,354
<i>The whole city
would be connected</i>

108
00:09:08,354 --> 00:09:13,888
<i>by a continuous main street
running around the outside rim.</i>

109
00:09:20,387 --> 00:09:22,721
<i>The farms and animals
would be housed</i>

110
00:09:22,721 --> 00:09:26,254
<i>in different layers
around the inner ring.</i>

111
00:09:26,254 --> 00:09:27,788
<i>Life would depend</i>

112
00:09:27,788 --> 00:09:33,320
<i>upon a continuously recycled
supply of air and water.</i>

113
00:09:36,421 --> 00:09:39,854
<i>The spinning outer rings
would be connected</i>

114
00:09:39,854 --> 00:09:41,487
<i>by four giant spokes</i>

115
00:09:41,487 --> 00:09:46,087
<i>to a stationary zero-gravity
hub in the center.</i>

116
00:09:46,087 --> 00:09:49,087
<i>This was the entrance
to our port</i>

117
00:09:49,087 --> 00:09:50,920
<i>where spacecraft dock.</i>

118
00:09:53,888 --> 00:09:56,920
<i>The entire perimeter
of the structure</i>

119
00:09:56,920 --> 00:10:01,020
<i>would be encased
in 10 million tons of moon rock</i>

120
00:10:01,020 --> 00:10:04,454
<i>to protect us
from cosmic radiation.</i>

121
00:10:11,053 --> 00:10:14,053
<i>A giant mirror
would float nearby</i>

122
00:10:14,053 --> 00:10:17,721
<i>to bathe the city
in reflected light.</i>

123
00:10:25,687 --> 00:10:31,854
<i>At last, after nearly 30 years,
our city was complete.</i>

124
00:10:38,987 --> 00:10:44,320
<i>With each transport from Earth,
new citizens arrived.</i>

125
00:10:46,920 --> 00:10:48,920
<i>We captured an asteroid</i>

126
00:10:48,921 --> 00:10:53,487
<i>to mine its metals and fuels
for our growing fleet of ships.</i>

127
00:10:56,320 --> 00:11:00,220
<i>Our dream
of settling the outer planets</i>

128
00:11:00,220 --> 00:11:02,487
<i>was soon to be realized.</i>

129
00:11:06,170 --> 00:11:09,271
[CHILDREN SQUEALING IN DELIGHT]

130
00:11:09,271 --> 00:11:12,104
<i>Inside the city's
protective skin,</i>

131
00:11:12,104 --> 00:11:15,471
<i>the population flourished
and grew.</i>

132
00:11:15,471 --> 00:11:20,870
<i>By the time I was seven,
there were 10,000 of us here.</i>

133
00:11:20,870 --> 00:11:24,937
<i>We modeled our neighborhood
after small towns on Earth.</i>

134
00:11:24,937 --> 00:11:26,937
[KIDS LAUGHING]

135
00:11:26,937 --> 00:11:29,136
<i>There were sensors everywhere
which could detect</i>

136
00:11:29,137 --> 00:11:34,804
<i>any sign of contamination
or imbalance in the air supply.</i>

137
00:11:34,804 --> 00:11:37,637
<i>Most days, my mother would come
by the playground</i>

138
00:11:37,637 --> 00:11:39,204
<i>on her way home from work.</i>

139
00:11:39,204 --> 00:11:40,838
<i>She was a doctor</i>

140
00:11:40,838 --> 00:11:43,938
<i>and had been one of the first
people selected to come here.</i>

141
00:11:43,938 --> 00:11:45,504
Eric.

142
00:11:45,504 --> 00:11:46,871
See you soon.
How's your hand?

143
00:11:46,871 --> 00:11:48,170
<i>CHIEKO:
She seemed to be friends</i>

144
00:11:48,170 --> 00:11:49,604
<i>with just about everybody.</i>

145
00:11:51,037 --> 00:11:52,037
Can you...?

146
00:11:52,037 --> 00:11:53,904
Good stuff!

147
00:11:53,904 --> 00:11:55,671
<i>CHIEKO: Her father--
my grandfather--</i>

148
00:11:55,671 --> 00:11:57,970
<i>was a pioneer founder of L5.</i>

149
00:11:59,037 --> 00:12:00,604
Oh, Chieko!

150
00:12:02,571 --> 00:12:03,970
What's this, Mom?

151
00:12:03,970 --> 00:12:05,771
Well, it was supposed
to be a surprise,

152
00:12:05,771 --> 00:12:07,571
but you're a little
too fast for me.

153
00:12:07,571 --> 00:12:08,571
Do you like it?

154
00:12:08,571 --> 00:12:09,804
I love it. Thank you.

155
00:12:09,804 --> 00:12:10,838
You're welcome.

156
00:12:10,838 --> 00:12:12,270
[WHISTLING]

157
00:12:15,704 --> 00:12:17,537
<i>CHIEKO:
My father was
a flight commander,</i>

158
00:12:17,537 --> 00:12:19,838
<i>an engineer.</i>

159
00:12:19,838 --> 00:12:23,037
<i>He'd explored almost all
of the inner planets,</i>

160
00:12:23,037 --> 00:12:25,204
<i>and now he was designing
an expedition</i>

161
00:12:25,204 --> 00:12:27,404
<i>to the Neptune system.</i>

162
00:12:27,404 --> 00:12:29,070
<i>When we wasn't working,</i>

163
00:12:29,070 --> 00:12:33,270
<i>you could almost always
find him at home
in the kitchen.</i>

164
00:12:33,270 --> 00:12:34,871
<i>Every kitchen at L5</i>

165
00:12:34,871 --> 00:12:37,671
<i>had a built-in
hydroponic garden.</i>

166
00:12:37,671 --> 00:12:39,137
[BEEPING]

167
00:12:45,270 --> 00:12:49,370
<i>The big farms on the inner ring
were hydroponic too,</i>

168
00:12:49,370 --> 00:12:52,003
<i>though sometimes
we used moon soil.</i>

169
00:12:54,070 --> 00:12:56,037
<i>What can I do
now, Nancy?</i>

170
00:12:56,037 --> 00:12:58,571
<i>You can help me
collect the cucumbers.</i>

171
00:12:58,571 --> 00:13:01,437
<i>CHIEKO: In many ways,
it was just like Earth here.</i>

172
00:13:01,437 --> 00:13:03,237
<i>We grew all kinds
of fruits and vegetables</i>

173
00:13:03,237 --> 00:13:05,070
<i>as they do,</i>

174
00:13:05,070 --> 00:13:07,170
<i>but in space, we could control</i>

175
00:13:07,170 --> 00:13:09,771
<i>the amount of sunlight
and the seasons</i>

176
00:13:09,771 --> 00:13:12,671
<i>so that everything was
available all year round.</i>

177
00:13:19,137 --> 00:13:22,003
<i>I loved to grow things.</i>

178
00:13:22,003 --> 00:13:26,070
<i>Back then, I wanted
to be a farmer.</i>

179
00:13:30,737 --> 00:13:32,204
[CHICKENS CLUCKING,
GOATS BLEATING]

180
00:13:35,037 --> 00:13:36,304
<i>Here on level two,</i>

181
00:13:36,304 --> 00:13:41,604
<i>all of the farms fit
into only 150 acres.</i>

182
00:13:41,604 --> 00:13:45,571
<i>We raised the usual animals,
but not very many cows.</i>

183
00:13:45,571 --> 00:13:47,571
<i>They took up too much space.</i>

184
00:13:47,571 --> 00:13:49,204
<i>Hi, Alice. Hi, Andy.</i>

185
00:13:57,604 --> 00:13:58,537
<i>Come on.</i>

186
00:14:00,437 --> 00:14:01,938
<i>Good girl.</i>

187
00:14:03,571 --> 00:14:04,504
[BEEPING]

188
00:14:10,003 --> 00:14:11,737
[CHICKS PEEPING]

189
00:14:14,737 --> 00:14:16,237
Hi, duckies.

190
00:14:17,637 --> 00:14:19,137
<i>CHIEKO:
Of course,</i>

191
00:14:19,137 --> 00:14:21,671
<i>I visited Earth farms
on virtual trips,</i>

192
00:14:21,671 --> 00:14:25,304
<i>but still, I often wondered
what it would really be like</i>

193
00:14:25,304 --> 00:14:28,804
<i>to lie in a field
and watch the clouds roll by.</i>

194
00:14:32,137 --> 00:14:36,137
<i>I knew all about Earth's giant
oceans and rivers,</i>

195
00:14:36,137 --> 00:14:39,571
<i>but it was hard to imagine
so much water.</i>

196
00:14:39,571 --> 00:14:43,504
<i>Every drop of ours had to be
imported and recycled.</i>

197
00:14:46,437 --> 00:14:51,504
<i>L5 was a world
of perfect harmony and balance.</i>

198
00:14:51,504 --> 00:14:54,938
<i>Then everything changed.</i>

199
00:14:56,237 --> 00:14:58,571
MAN: I've been doing
some calculations...

200
00:14:58,571 --> 00:15:00,537
<i>CHIEKO:
It began one day</i>

201
00:15:00,537 --> 00:15:02,804
<i>when I went to visit
my grandfather at his lab.</i>

202
00:15:02,804 --> 00:15:05,804
<i>I was surprised
to see my father there too.</i>

203
00:15:05,804 --> 00:15:07,404
FATHER: The amount of fuel
it would take

204
00:15:07,404 --> 00:15:08,771
to lift the water...

205
00:15:08,771 --> 00:15:10,704
<i>CHIEKO: I'll never forget
what I heard.</i>

206
00:15:10,704 --> 00:15:14,103
<i>Our life-support systems
had reached their limit.</i>

207
00:15:14,103 --> 00:15:16,737
<i>Unless more water
could be found soon,</i>

208
00:15:16,737 --> 00:15:19,604
<i>there wouldn't be enough
to sustain us all.</i>

209
00:15:22,237 --> 00:15:24,604
<i>I have something
to show you, Mori.</i>

210
00:15:24,604 --> 00:15:28,270
<i>CHIEKO: My grandfather
was L5's senior scientist.</i>

211
00:15:28,270 --> 00:15:31,970
<i>He'd been searching
for a solution to our dilemma.</i>

212
00:15:31,970 --> 00:15:33,571
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Comet velocity--</i>

213
00:15:33,571 --> 00:15:35,304
<i>22.3 kilometers per second.</i>

214
00:15:35,304 --> 00:15:37,637
You know,
this just might work.

215
00:15:37,637 --> 00:15:39,137
It's an ideal size.

216
00:15:39,137 --> 00:15:43,671
We wouldn't have
to change the orbit very much.

217
00:15:43,671 --> 00:15:45,571
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Hinckley's diameter</i>

218
00:15:45,571 --> 00:15:47,137
<i>is 5.72 kilometers.</i>

219
00:15:47,137 --> 00:15:49,404
<i>CHIEKO:
Almost 500 million miles</i>

220
00:15:49,404 --> 00:15:50,970
<i>away from us,</i>

221
00:15:50,970 --> 00:15:53,537
<i>a comet was approaching
Jupiter.</i>

222
00:15:53,537 --> 00:15:56,704
<i>The tumbling mass at its core</i>

223
00:15:56,704 --> 00:16:01,103
<i>was actually
a giant reservoir of water.</i>

224
00:16:13,704 --> 00:16:17,404
All right...
this is Jupiter.

225
00:16:17,404 --> 00:16:19,204
This is the path
of the comet.

226
00:16:19,204 --> 00:16:21,571
If we were to put a rocket
on the comet

227
00:16:21,571 --> 00:16:23,170
and divert it
towards Earth,

228
00:16:23,170 --> 00:16:25,103
it would pass L5
every few years

229
00:16:25,103 --> 00:16:26,604
and supply us

230
00:16:26,604 --> 00:16:28,204
with all the water
we would ever need.

231
00:16:28,204 --> 00:16:29,604
Still, it would take
a powerful rocket

232
00:16:29,604 --> 00:16:31,270
to change the direction
that much.

233
00:16:31,270 --> 00:16:33,103
No, no, no,
not at all.

234
00:16:33,103 --> 00:16:34,970
Jupiter's gravity
has more power

235
00:16:34,970 --> 00:16:37,003
than any rocket
we could ever dream of,

236
00:16:37,003 --> 00:16:39,370
and I have the data
from a hundred years ago

237
00:16:39,370 --> 00:16:40,737
to prove it.

238
00:16:40,737 --> 00:16:43,804
Chieko,
lend me a hand here.

239
00:16:43,804 --> 00:16:45,804
Come and help me
explain something

240
00:16:45,804 --> 00:16:47,137
to your father...

241
00:16:47,137 --> 00:16:48,771
<i>CHIEKO:
My grandfather</i>

242
00:16:48,771 --> 00:16:51,637
<i>had led the first expeditions
to the moons of Jupiter</i>

243
00:16:51,637 --> 00:16:53,671
<i>many years before.</i>

244
00:16:53,671 --> 00:16:55,137
<i>Now that my father</i>

245
00:16:55,137 --> 00:16:57,237
<i>had succeeded him
as flight commander,</i>

246
00:16:57,237 --> 00:16:58,604
<i>Grandpa had turned
his attention</i>

247
00:16:58,604 --> 00:16:59,904
<i>to the study of comets.</i>

248
00:17:04,437 --> 00:17:06,604
What is it?

249
00:17:06,604 --> 00:17:08,637
GRANDFATHER:
Now, this is Jupiter

250
00:17:08,637 --> 00:17:10,404
as it was seen

251
00:17:10,404 --> 00:17:12,137
by a spacecraft
called Galileo

252
00:17:12,137 --> 00:17:14,037
<i>100 years ago.</i>

253
00:17:14,037 --> 00:17:16,504
CHIEKO:: Is that
another comet?

254
00:17:16,504 --> 00:17:18,437
Indeed it is.

255
00:17:18,437 --> 00:17:20,504
A comet called
Shoemaker-Levy 9

256
00:17:20,504 --> 00:17:22,704
was passing nearby.

257
00:17:22,704 --> 00:17:24,437
[EXPLOSION]

258
00:17:26,204 --> 00:17:28,204
What happened?

259
00:17:28,204 --> 00:17:30,337
Jupiter's gravity
is so powerful

260
00:17:30,337 --> 00:17:32,003
it broke
the comet apart

261
00:17:32,003 --> 00:17:34,938
and sucked the pieces
into its atmosphere.

262
00:17:36,537 --> 00:17:39,737
Now, if this force
was strong enough

263
00:17:39,737 --> 00:17:42,704
to pull Shoemaker-Levy
off course...

264
00:17:42,704 --> 00:17:44,671
MORI: Then we could use
some of that power

265
00:17:44,671 --> 00:17:46,237
to change the orbit
of our comet.

266
00:17:46,237 --> 00:17:47,804
Precisely.

267
00:17:49,037 --> 00:17:50,704
So you see,
Mori,

268
00:17:50,704 --> 00:17:53,304
Jupiter will do most
of the work for us.

269
00:17:53,304 --> 00:17:54,704
All we need to do

270
00:17:54,704 --> 00:17:56,904
is attach a small rocket
to the comet

271
00:17:56,904 --> 00:17:58,237
to get it there.

272
00:17:58,237 --> 00:17:59,704
What do you think?

273
00:18:01,404 --> 00:18:03,537
<i>CHIEKO:
So began the first attempt</i>

274
00:18:03,537 --> 00:18:06,437
<i>to capture a comet.</i>

275
00:18:06,437 --> 00:18:08,838
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Transport at 1.3 A.U.</i>

276
00:18:08,838 --> 00:18:12,103
<i>CHIEKO: A robot rocket
was launched from L5.</i>

277
00:18:12,103 --> 00:18:14,204
<i>When it found the comet,
it would attach itself</i>

278
00:18:14,204 --> 00:18:17,103
<i>and wait for the command
to fire.</i>

279
00:18:52,204 --> 00:18:56,037
<i>Four months later,
the critical time had come.</i>

280
00:18:58,070 --> 00:19:01,737
<i>The rocket
had now reached the comet.</i>

281
00:19:01,737 --> 00:19:03,537
<i>They had sent the command
to fire.</i>

282
00:19:03,537 --> 00:19:05,904
We should have seen
a vector change by now.

283
00:19:05,904 --> 00:19:07,871
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Malfunction. Negative berth.</i>

284
00:19:09,237 --> 00:19:10,838
There's no power.

285
00:19:10,838 --> 00:19:12,737
There's no motion
at all.

286
00:19:15,003 --> 00:19:16,537
Plasma traps are okay.

287
00:19:17,571 --> 00:19:19,904
Pressure's fine.

288
00:19:19,904 --> 00:19:21,237
I don't get it.

289
00:19:21,237 --> 00:19:23,003
Let's run the
ignition simulation.

290
00:19:23,003 --> 00:19:24,404
That may tell us
something.

291
00:19:24,404 --> 00:19:26,437
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Autosequence start.</i>

292
00:19:26,437 --> 00:19:28,771
See, there's nothing
that could shake loose.

293
00:19:28,771 --> 00:19:30,604
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Negative berth.</i>

294
00:19:30,604 --> 00:19:32,270
Wait a second.

295
00:19:32,270 --> 00:19:35,270
[WHOOSH]

296
00:19:35,270 --> 00:19:36,970
Could be
the nozzle.

297
00:19:36,970 --> 00:19:38,204
<i>CHIEKO:
A chunk of debris</i>

298
00:19:38,204 --> 00:19:40,771
<i>was jammed
in the rocket's exhaust.</i>

299
00:19:40,771 --> 00:19:44,003
<i>Unless they could clear it
and fire the rocket,</i>

300
00:19:44,003 --> 00:19:46,137
<i>the comet would continue
on its path,</i>

301
00:19:46,137 --> 00:19:47,604
<i>forever lost.</i>

302
00:19:47,604 --> 00:19:50,938
Shut down
by one speck of dirt.

303
00:19:50,938 --> 00:19:53,938
Not necessarily.

304
00:19:53,938 --> 00:19:56,437
What do you
propose we do?

305
00:19:56,437 --> 00:19:58,270
I could go and fix it.

306
00:19:58,270 --> 00:20:00,070
You can't be serious.

307
00:20:00,070 --> 00:20:04,471
No one has ever even thought
about landing on a comet.

308
00:20:04,471 --> 00:20:05,537
Why not?

309
00:20:05,537 --> 00:20:06,938
Icould be there
in two months,

310
00:20:06,938 --> 00:20:08,404
clean everything up,

311
00:20:08,404 --> 00:20:10,904
and you'd still be in time
for the course correction.

312
00:20:10,904 --> 00:20:12,671
<i>CHIEKO:
And so my father began</i>

313
00:20:12,671 --> 00:20:14,404
<i>to prepare for
the mission of his life.</i>

314
00:20:18,471 --> 00:20:20,604
<i>I was too young to grasp</i>

315
00:20:20,604 --> 00:20:22,838
<i>how dangerous
his mission really was.</i>

316
00:20:22,838 --> 00:20:25,571
<i>I was busy playing
with my friends on Earth.</i>

317
00:20:25,571 --> 00:20:28,137
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Earth call for Chieko.</i>

318
00:20:28,137 --> 00:20:29,804
<i>GIRL: Hi, Chieko.</i>

319
00:20:29,804 --> 00:20:30,804
Pips. What's up?

320
00:20:30,804 --> 00:20:33,204
<i>Not much.
What you doing?</i>

321
00:20:33,204 --> 00:20:34,838
<i>CHIEKO:
Sometimes I would visit them,</i>

322
00:20:34,838 --> 00:20:36,237
<i>and sometimes they'd come here.</i>

323
00:20:36,237 --> 00:20:37,838
<i>Let's go
somewhere else today.</i>

324
00:20:37,838 --> 00:20:39,170
<i>Like where?</i>

325
00:20:39,170 --> 00:20:40,871
<i>Um... I don't know.</i>

326
00:20:40,871 --> 00:20:42,504
<i>We could go
to the zoo.</i>

327
00:20:42,504 --> 00:20:44,170
<i>I've got an idea.</i>

328
00:20:44,170 --> 00:20:46,337
<i>Meet me on channel 29, okay?</i>

329
00:20:46,337 --> 00:20:48,337
<i>Okay,
see you there.</i>

330
00:20:48,337 --> 00:20:50,070
[SPEAKERPHONE DISCONNECTS]

331
00:20:50,070 --> 00:20:51,537
<i>CHIEKO:
With virtual travel,</i>

332
00:20:51,537 --> 00:20:55,170
<i>we could meet
anywhere we wanted.</i>

333
00:20:55,170 --> 00:20:57,504
<i>Once you'd scanned in
your destination,</i>

334
00:20:57,504 --> 00:21:00,504
<i>you could bring in your friends
to explore it with you.</i>

335
00:21:00,504 --> 00:21:02,137
[WHOOSH]

336
00:21:10,504 --> 00:21:13,204
[CHILDREN LAUGHING]

337
00:21:13,204 --> 00:21:14,671
Frosty's
looking good.

338
00:21:16,003 --> 00:21:17,771
Brilliant, Chieko.

339
00:21:17,771 --> 00:21:20,671
I got Chas, Matty,
and Kristen to come too.

340
00:21:22,838 --> 00:21:24,003
Hey, Chieko.

341
00:21:24,003 --> 00:21:26,904
How do you like it?

342
00:21:26,904 --> 00:21:28,504
Wow! I love it.

343
00:21:28,504 --> 00:21:30,070
Look what I found.

344
00:21:30,070 --> 00:21:31,070
It's fantastic.

345
00:21:31,070 --> 00:21:32,070
Yippee!

346
00:21:32,070 --> 00:21:34,070
This is so fun.

347
00:21:34,070 --> 00:21:36,070
Let's play hide-and-seek.

348
00:21:36,070 --> 00:21:37,237
Yeah.

349
00:21:37,237 --> 00:21:39,571
Bet you can't catch me.

350
00:21:39,571 --> 00:21:41,003
ALL:
Bet we can.

351
00:21:41,003 --> 00:21:43,103
Ready or not, here we come.

352
00:21:44,504 --> 00:21:46,771
Here I am.

353
00:21:46,771 --> 00:21:48,604
Where'd she go?

354
00:21:48,604 --> 00:21:50,504
Catch me.

355
00:21:50,504 --> 00:21:51,504
Got you.

356
00:21:51,504 --> 00:21:52,571
Oh, goody.

357
00:21:52,571 --> 00:21:55,437
How'd you do that?

358
00:21:55,437 --> 00:21:59,103
I know. Let's play
knights and dragons.

359
00:21:59,103 --> 00:22:00,604
Yeah, what should I be?

360
00:22:00,604 --> 00:22:02,270
Yeah, great idea.

361
00:22:02,270 --> 00:22:03,970
I'm going to be the queen.

362
00:22:03,970 --> 00:22:05,304
Aren't these great?

363
00:22:05,304 --> 00:22:06,704
Do I look good?

364
00:22:06,704 --> 00:22:08,037
How do I look?

365
00:22:08,037 --> 00:22:09,771
Don't I look beautiful?

366
00:22:09,771 --> 00:22:11,103
What's wrong?

367
00:22:11,103 --> 00:22:14,137
Sorry, guys, I got to go.

368
00:22:14,137 --> 00:22:15,404
See you.

369
00:22:15,404 --> 00:22:17,003
Bye.

370
00:22:18,471 --> 00:22:21,137
Bye, Chieko.

371
00:22:21,137 --> 00:22:22,337
[WHOOSH]

372
00:22:23,970 --> 00:22:25,471
MORI: Did I say
something wrong?

373
00:22:25,471 --> 00:22:26,537
MOTHER: No.

374
00:22:26,537 --> 00:22:27,537
What is it, then?

375
00:22:27,537 --> 00:22:28,537
Nothing.

376
00:22:28,537 --> 00:22:30,103
Tell me
what's the matter.

377
00:22:30,103 --> 00:22:32,604
You know perfectly well
what's the matter.

378
00:22:32,604 --> 00:22:34,003
Come on, Jenny.

379
00:22:34,003 --> 00:22:35,604
It's no different
from my last six flights.

380
00:22:35,604 --> 00:22:36,838
There's nothing
to worry about.

381
00:22:36,838 --> 00:22:38,337
You know
as well as I do

382
00:22:38,337 --> 00:22:40,337
nobody's ever done this
before.

383
00:22:40,337 --> 00:22:42,003
You have no idea
what could happen.

384
00:22:42,003 --> 00:22:44,070
Well, I know what
will happen if I don't go.

385
00:22:44,070 --> 00:22:46,737
We can just chuck everything
we've been trying to do here

386
00:22:46,737 --> 00:22:48,037
and go back home
to Earth.

387
00:22:48,037 --> 00:22:50,103
You know that's not
what I meant.

388
00:22:51,604 --> 00:22:53,437
[WATER RUNNING]

389
00:22:53,437 --> 00:22:54,537
It's about time.

390
00:22:54,537 --> 00:22:56,270
Mom's been
calling you.

391
00:22:58,604 --> 00:23:00,237
What about a story?

392
00:23:00,237 --> 00:23:01,938
Would you like that?

393
00:23:01,938 --> 00:23:03,337
Why don't you hop
into your jammies

394
00:23:03,337 --> 00:23:04,571
and do your teeth?

395
00:23:04,571 --> 00:23:06,604
Daddy will come
and tuck you in, okay?

396
00:23:16,938 --> 00:23:20,604
<i>CHIEKO:
I'd never heard my parents talk
that way before.</i>

397
00:23:20,604 --> 00:23:24,170
<i>I didn't understand
what my father had meant</i>

398
00:23:24,170 --> 00:23:26,304
<i>when he said
"go back home to Earth."</i>

399
00:23:29,771 --> 00:23:32,970
<i>Even if I did have lots
of friends and family there,</i>

400
00:23:32,970 --> 00:23:35,737
<i>my home was here at L5,</i>

401
00:23:35,737 --> 00:23:39,370
<i>and I had never, ever thought
of leaving it,</i>

402
00:23:39,370 --> 00:23:42,904
<i>even for a planet
as beautiful as Earth.</i>

403
00:23:51,938 --> 00:23:54,137
I was beginning to think
you forgot all about me.

404
00:23:54,137 --> 00:23:55,137
Night.

405
00:23:55,137 --> 00:23:56,804
[BEEPING]

406
00:23:56,804 --> 00:24:00,204
Now, what story
shall I tell you?

407
00:24:01,304 --> 00:24:04,304
Shall we go to Io
or back to the whales?

408
00:24:04,304 --> 00:24:05,471
Daddy?

409
00:24:05,471 --> 00:24:06,970
Yeah?

410
00:24:06,970 --> 00:24:08,637
What is it, Chieko?

411
00:24:08,637 --> 00:24:11,471
You'll come back,
won't you?

412
00:24:11,471 --> 00:24:12,704
I'm right here.

413
00:24:12,704 --> 00:24:14,204
I'm not going
anywhere.

414
00:24:14,204 --> 00:24:18,137
No, I mean, will you
come back from the comet?

415
00:24:18,137 --> 00:24:20,471
Of course I will.

416
00:24:20,471 --> 00:24:24,471
You know me.
Piece of cake.

417
00:24:24,471 --> 00:24:28,838
And I'll bring you back
a real snowball.

418
00:24:28,838 --> 00:24:30,337
Deal?

419
00:24:30,337 --> 00:24:31,337
Deal.

420
00:24:31,337 --> 00:24:32,871
Okay.

421
00:24:35,170 --> 00:24:41,170
Now, once upon a time,
there was a big, blue whale,

422
00:24:41,170 --> 00:24:45,337
and he swam and he swam
and he swam

423
00:24:45,337 --> 00:24:47,671
until he reached
the magic...

424
00:24:47,671 --> 00:24:49,604
[SHIP BLASTS OFF]

425
00:24:53,103 --> 00:24:56,204
<i>GRANDFATHER:
Mori, we're with you
all the way.</i>

426
00:24:56,204 --> 00:24:57,370
<i>Good luck.</i>

427
00:25:17,904 --> 00:25:19,870
<i>CHIEKO:
From the moment he left,</i>

428
00:25:19,870 --> 00:25:22,071
<i>things just weren't the same
for me.</i>

429
00:25:22,071 --> 00:25:26,071
<i>It would be weeks
before he reached the comet,</i>

430
00:25:26,071 --> 00:25:27,904
<i>but at least we could talk
to him</i>

431
00:25:27,904 --> 00:25:29,104
<i>before he moved
beyond the range</i>

432
00:25:29,104 --> 00:25:31,337
<i>of realtime communication.</i>

433
00:25:31,337 --> 00:25:33,737
<i>MORI:
No deltas to the flight plan.</i>

434
00:25:33,737 --> 00:25:35,770
<i>Everything's nominal.</i>

435
00:25:35,770 --> 00:25:37,937
<i>On time, on course.</i>

436
00:25:37,937 --> 00:25:39,770
<i>[STATIC]</i>

437
00:25:39,770 --> 00:25:42,538
<i>A little more solar activity
than we predicted,</i>

438
00:25:42,538 --> 00:25:45,404
<i>but I don't think
it's anything to worry about.</i>

439
00:25:45,404 --> 00:25:47,937
<i>I'll keep an eye on it.</i>

440
00:25:47,937 --> 00:25:49,438
<i>How's Chieko?</i>

441
00:25:49,438 --> 00:25:51,104
<i>Chieko's just fine.</i>

442
00:25:51,104 --> 00:25:53,770
<i>MORI: I'm getting fat
on all those cookies she made.</i>

443
00:25:53,770 --> 00:25:55,271
<i>I miss you.</i>

444
00:25:55,271 --> 00:25:57,104
I miss you too, Mori.

445
00:25:57,104 --> 00:25:59,037
<i>CHIEKO: My mother
put on a brave face for me.</i>

446
00:26:01,104 --> 00:26:03,037
[GOATS BLEATING]

447
00:26:06,438 --> 00:26:11,637
<i>We both tried in our own ways
to keep our spirits up,</i>

448
00:26:11,637 --> 00:26:14,637
<i>but I couldn't help thinking
about my father</i>

449
00:26:14,637 --> 00:26:16,404
<i>and how far away he was.</i>

450
00:26:20,137 --> 00:26:21,570
Bye-bye.

451
00:26:28,137 --> 00:26:29,804
<i>CHIEKO:
Grandpa was the only one</i>

452
00:26:29,804 --> 00:26:31,670
<i>who really knew</i>

453
00:26:31,670 --> 00:26:33,904
<i>how perilous my father's
journey had now become.</i>

454
00:26:35,137 --> 00:26:37,837
<i>With each passing
day and night,</i>

455
00:26:37,837 --> 00:26:40,071
<i>the solar storm
was intensifying.</i>

456
00:26:45,337 --> 00:26:47,471
<i>If transmission was cut off</i>

457
00:26:47,471 --> 00:26:50,104
<i>and my father's ship
malfunctioned,</i>

458
00:26:50,104 --> 00:26:52,337
<i>we would never know.</i>

459
00:26:52,337 --> 00:26:54,404
<i>At such a great distance,</i>

460
00:26:54,404 --> 00:26:57,603
<i>a rescue team
might never reach him in time.</i>

461
00:27:01,237 --> 00:27:04,538
<i>MORI: Closing at 10 meters
per second.</i>

462
00:27:04,538 --> 00:27:08,071
<i>CHIEKO: I'll always remember
the day he landed.</i>

463
00:27:08,071 --> 00:27:10,304
<i>We gathered together to watch.</i>

464
00:27:20,904 --> 00:27:22,504
<i>MORI: 100 meters.</i>

465
00:27:24,237 --> 00:27:26,737
<i>90...</i>

466
00:27:26,737 --> 00:27:28,337
<i>80...</i>

467
00:27:28,337 --> 00:27:29,804
<i>70...</i>

468
00:27:33,404 --> 00:27:34,804
<i>60...</i>

469
00:27:46,371 --> 00:27:48,071
<i>Ten meters...</i>

470
00:27:48,071 --> 00:27:49,970
<i>Nine...</i>

471
00:27:49,970 --> 00:27:51,438
<i>Eight...</i>

472
00:27:51,438 --> 00:27:52,970
<i>Seven...</i>

473
00:27:52,970 --> 00:27:54,603
<i>Six...</i>

474
00:27:54,603 --> 00:27:56,104
<i>Five meters...</i>

475
00:27:58,371 --> 00:28:00,204
<i>Three...</i>

476
00:28:00,204 --> 00:28:01,637
<i>Two...</i>

477
00:28:01,637 --> 00:28:03,171
<i>One.</i>

478
00:28:04,271 --> 00:28:06,271
<i>I'm on it.</i>

479
00:28:06,271 --> 00:28:07,504
<i>Yes!</i>

480
00:28:12,404 --> 00:28:14,237
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
EMV pod separation maneuver</i>

481
00:28:14,237 --> 00:28:15,937
<i>in five seconds...</i>

482
00:28:15,937 --> 00:28:20,171
<i>four, three, two, one.</i>

483
00:28:20,171 --> 00:28:21,504
<i>Mark.</i>

484
00:28:25,037 --> 00:28:27,037
<i>EMV pod is clear.</i>

485
00:28:50,438 --> 00:28:52,870
[ALARM SOUNDING]

486
00:28:52,870 --> 00:28:55,570
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Stabilizer malfunction.</i>

487
00:28:55,570 --> 00:28:57,504
<i>Manual guidance system enabled.</i>

488
00:29:14,071 --> 00:29:16,237
<i>MORI:
Okay, I'm going in.</i>

489
00:29:42,203 --> 00:29:45,570
<i>MORI: I've located
the problem here.</i>

490
00:29:45,570 --> 00:29:47,704
<i>I'll have to try
a manual disable.</i>

491
00:29:49,104 --> 00:29:50,771
<i>Did you copy that?</i>

492
00:29:50,771 --> 00:29:53,170
<i>A manual disable.</i>

493
00:29:53,170 --> 00:29:55,104
<i>This engine is still armed.</i>

494
00:29:55,104 --> 00:29:57,437
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Warning.
Minimum safety distance.</i>

495
00:29:57,437 --> 00:29:59,104
<i>Warning.</i>

496
00:29:59,104 --> 00:30:01,203
<i>Propulsion system is armed.</i>

497
00:30:01,203 --> 00:30:03,570
<i>Standing by
for your instructions.</i>

498
00:30:03,570 --> 00:30:05,637
<i>COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
Detecting ionic interference.</i>

499
00:30:06,971 --> 00:30:08,537
<i>Severe solar interference.</i>

500
00:30:08,537 --> 00:30:11,470
<i>CHIEKO: Grandpa's worst fears
were coming true.</i>

501
00:30:11,470 --> 00:30:16,138
<i>A massive solar flare erupted,
jamming all the transmissions.</i>

502
00:30:16,138 --> 00:30:18,138
[SIREN BEEPING]

503
00:30:18,138 --> 00:30:20,270
Mori, this is L5.

504
00:30:20,270 --> 00:30:24,138
We've had a loss
of signal and telemetry here.

505
00:30:24,138 --> 00:30:25,637
Please advise your status.

506
00:30:25,637 --> 00:30:27,404
<i>CHIEKO: Then we lost contact
altogether.</i>

507
00:30:31,138 --> 00:30:36,104
<i>We sent out call after call,
and then we waited...</i>

508
00:30:37,604 --> 00:30:40,337
<i>and waited.</i>

509
00:30:40,337 --> 00:30:43,937
<i>It seemed to be the longest day
of my life.</i>

510
00:30:49,337 --> 00:30:52,671
<i>By nightfall, still nothing.</i>

511
00:30:52,671 --> 00:30:54,104
GRANDFATHER:
We are standing by.

512
00:30:55,871 --> 00:30:57,937
[COMPUTERIZED VOICE
SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

513
00:31:00,437 --> 00:31:02,937
[STATIC AND BUZZING]

514
00:31:02,937 --> 00:31:04,504
Mori!

515
00:31:04,504 --> 00:31:08,570
L5... ignition confirmed.

516
00:31:10,537 --> 00:31:13,937
Mori, vector change confirms.

517
00:31:15,038 --> 00:31:16,971
It's moving, Mori.

518
00:31:16,971 --> 00:31:18,604
The comet is moving.

519
00:31:18,604 --> 00:31:21,604
<i>CHIEKO: Telemetry showed
the rocket had fired,</i>

520
00:31:21,604 --> 00:31:23,937
<i>but there was no word
from my father.</i>

521
00:31:23,937 --> 00:31:25,804
[COMPUTERIZED VOICE
SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

522
00:31:29,570 --> 00:31:31,604
<i>MORI:
L5, are you there?</i>

523
00:31:31,604 --> 00:31:33,604
<i>Well, I just made it
in the nick of time.</i>

524
00:31:33,604 --> 00:31:35,971
<i>Looked like a beautiful bird.</i>

525
00:31:39,804 --> 00:31:43,470
<i>Looks like I'll be home
for Chieko's birthday.</i>

526
00:31:43,470 --> 00:31:45,038
<i>See you soon.</i>

527
00:31:45,038 --> 00:31:46,971
[LAUGHING]

528
00:31:51,837 --> 00:31:54,071
<i>CHIEKO:
I knew then</i>

529
00:31:54,071 --> 00:31:56,104
<i>that we would never forget
this day.</i>

530
00:31:56,104 --> 00:32:00,004
<i>The comet and its water
were ours</i>

531
00:32:00,004 --> 00:32:03,671
<i>and the future of L5
looked bright.</i>

532
00:32:03,671 --> 00:32:05,170
[CHIEKO GIGGLES]

533
00:32:13,337 --> 00:32:17,704
CHIEKO: 30 years have passed
since my story began.

534
00:32:17,704 --> 00:32:21,370
<i>Our robots have retrieved
yet another piece of the comet</i>

535
00:32:21,370 --> 00:32:23,871
<i>and are bringing it home
to process</i>

536
00:32:23,871 --> 00:32:28,071
<i>exactly as my grandfather
had planned.</i>

537
00:32:31,370 --> 00:32:37,704
<i>Not long ago,
I was elected mayor of L5.</i>

538
00:32:37,704 --> 00:32:40,637
<i>We have built
a second city here,</i>

539
00:32:40,637 --> 00:32:44,038
<i>and our port in space
is now 20,000 strong.</i>

540
00:32:46,537 --> 00:32:49,737
<i>Our dream has come true.</i>

541
00:32:49,737 --> 00:32:55,004
<i>At last, we are citizens
of the solar system.</i>

